  "prompt": "In movies that play in the US, tires of cars are always squeaking. Why?",
  "response": "The exaggerated sound of tires squeaking in movies is a staple of cinematic sound design, and it\u2019s used for several reasons:\n\n1. **Dramatic Effect**: The high-pitched squeal of tires adds excitement and intensity to a scene, whether it's a car chase, a sudden stop, or a quick getaway. It signals urgency, danger, or action to the audience.\n\n2. **Auditory Cue**: Squeaking tires serve as a sound cue to emphasize the movement or maneuver of a vehicle. In real life, tires don\u2019t always squeal when they should, but in movies, the sound helps the audience understand what\u2019s happening visually.\n\n3. **Exaggeration for Entertainment**: Real-life driving often lacks the dramatic flair that movies aim for. Squealing tires make ordinary actions, like turning a corner, seem more thrilling or skillful.\n\n4. **Sound Design Convention**: It\u2019s a long-standing Hollywood tradition. Audiences have come to expect certain sounds in specific situations, and squeaking tires are part of that cinematic language.\n\n5. **Reinforcing Character Traits**: In some cases, the sound of tires screeching can highlight a character\u2019s personality\u2014whether they\u2019re aggressive, reckless, or in a hurry.\n\nIn reality, tires only squeal under specific conditions, such as when a car is turning sharply, braking hard, or accelerating quickly on a slippery surface. In movies, however, these sounds are often added in post-production, regardless of whether they would occur in real life. It\u2019s one of many ways filmmakers enhance the storytelling experience. \ud83c\udfa5\ud83d\ude97",
